The consequences of resetting reference variables include:
- When all references to a particular object have been redirected or set to null, the associated object is freed. For example, given the following declarations:
a = Addr;
b = Addr;
If you then set both a and b to null, the original object for a is freed.
- When an object has been freed, any subsequent references to that object generate an error.

Some examples of using the 'is null' operator include the following:
